properties.abstract: The historic path leads high above the striking Zgen Gorge, with views of the surrounding peaks and the Landwasser mountain river, which finds its way through the narrow gorge. The hike offers variety in every respect for families, those interested in culture, nature enthusiasts and leisure hikers.
properties.description:
From Davos Glaris, the path climbs slightly and leads along the hill on the right side of the valley towards the Zgen Gorge. Initially on a forest road, the trail soon becomes narrower and plunges into the woods.

The middle section through the woods to the Steigwald via Hheggen, offers a varied view of the surrounding mountains and down into the impressive Zgen Gorge. The three-kilometre-long gorge between Davos Wiesen and Monstein was formed over centuries by the Landwasser River, which created a striking rocky landscape. Early on, the trail through the inaccessible gorge became an important trade connection for the people of Davos. In the years 14771848, what was produced from the Davos silver mine was transported via the old train route. Construction began on the old Zgenstrasse in 1870. This is still considered a work of art in road construction today.

On the opposite side of the slope, you can explore the village of Monstein, a picturesque Walser village in a sunny location, which is home to the highest beer brewery in Europe. Although the Zgenweg points towards the opposite slope from time to time, no noise can be heard from the main road.

The hiking trail winds through the forest and across the many steep ravines down to the sun-drenched terraced village of Davos Wiesen. A little later, you reach the small train station, from where you can take the Rhaetian Railway quickly and conveniently back to Davos. It is worth taking a short detour to the Wiesner Viaduct, the second highest bridge in the Rhaetian Railway network. This offers another perspective on the Zgen Gorge.
